@user1:
The `dataset_info.dataset_size` is the size of the dataset from `load_dataset`. If some users transform the dataset using `map` then `dataset_info.dataset_size` is not updated (we could add this feature though).
Therefore currently using `is_small_dataset(dataset_info.dataset_size)` can only be used in `load_dataset`, not in `load_from_disk`. Here, you could instead check for the size of the arrow file.

@author:
Yes @user1, you are right: dataset_size is always None when `load_from_disk` is called. However, the argument passed to `load_from_disk` is a directory (not an Arrow file) and it might contain multiple subdirectories (train, test), with multiple Arrow files. Should I make a scan and sum up all Arrow data file sizes?

@user1:
I think the `is_small_dataset` check can be done only in `Dataset.load_from_disk` (`datasets.load.load_from_disk` amd `DatasetDict.load_from_disk` can just pass the `keep_in_memory ` argument). So yes I think you just need to take the list of arrow files and sum their sizes.

In the code of `Dataset.load_from_disk` you can get the paths of the arrow files from `state["_data_files"]`.
For example the arrow files are used to load the table this way:

https://github.com/huggingface/datasets/blob/2a05294e2f8bc66983137797f213b325c78737b5/src/datasets/arrow_dataset.py#L654-L657


